description.plain:
Alex Lahey stated in an interview that she wrote this song to express:

the feeling of when you really like someone, you’re hanging out all the time, and the rest of your life falls by the wayside.

The song expresses this deep infatuation people have in new relationships. This can cause things that were once important such as work and family to be ignored, in order for the individual to give their undivided attention to their new love.

body.plain:
“You Don’t Think You Like People Like Me” was one of Alex Lahey’s earlier songs, getting her noticed.

Alex is openly gay, and it’s clear from the song that here she’s dealing with a bicurious/not sure “straight” woman.

annotations:
You don’t think you like people like me
 I know I’ve heard this one before

Lahey here is reflecting on what her lover has just told her. The woman Alex is with is bi-curious, but is unsure if she is a lesbian or just ‘experimenting’.
Often people experimenting state they are unsure if they are truly attracted to their same gender, or if it’s just a once off to see what they like.
And watch Mulholland Drive with you

David Lynch’s Mulholland Drive is one of the most award-winning and critically acclaimed lesbian movies. Its tagline was “A love story in the city of dreams”, and it has an ambiguous ending/meaning, much like the relationship Lahey finds herself in.

What’s that look on your tired face, honey?
 I’m getting tired, don’t find this funny
 Can we pick it up from where we started?
 Even if it leaves me broken-hearted
 What’s that look on your tired face, honey?
 I’m getting tired, I don’t find this funny
 You and I, you and I
 Oh-oh-oh-oh, oh-oh-oh-oh
When you’re hung up on somebody, vague responses can hurt more than clear bad ones. So Lahey is stating how she’d rather move on, because waiting is painful and tiring.
All I want is to have cleanskin wine
Cleanskin wine is generic, low cost wine sold without noting a winery or winemaker on the label. It’s comparable to “two buck Chuck” in America.
